<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<!--
  Cleartext (HTTP) is permitted app-wide. Why app-wide and not scoped:

  The endpoints that legitimately use http:// — the self-hosted sync server and a local AI
  endpoint — are addressed by a URL the user types at runtime (any host or bare IP, often a
  LAN address). Android's network-security-config can only pin cleartext to specific literal
  domains via <domain-config>; it can't allow it for "whatever the user enters" or for RFC-1918
  ranges. So there is no <domain-config> that expresses "the server the user configured", and a
  base-config toggle is the only mechanism that covers the feature.

  Why it's acceptable: the self-hosted server follows the Vaultwarden model (the user runs it,
  often on a trusted LAN without TLS). The sync payload is E2E-encrypted (zero-knowledge), SRP-6a
  never transmits the password, and its M2 authenticates the server; metadata is open by design.
  See docs/skerry-sync-design.md.

  Residual risk (documented, not eliminated by this file): over plain http:// a network MITM can
  read JWTs/metadata and hijack a session; a local AI endpoint sent secrets is likewise exposed.
  The in-app UI is the real backstop here — it warns on every http:// URL (sync setup, pairing
  join, AI endpoint) — and SECURITY.md § "Transport" spells out the trade-off. Whoever sets up
  HTTPS just points at https:// and gets encrypted transport with no config change.
-->
<network-security-config>
    <base-config cleartextTrafficPermitted="true" />
</network-security-config>
